      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <section id="what-is-knowledge-graph-optimisation" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What Knowledge Graph Optimisation Is</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Knowledge graph optimisation is the systematic process of building, verifying, and reinforcing your brand's entity record within the structured knowledge bases that AI systems use to understand the world.</strong>
          Where traditional SEO targets ranking algorithms, knowledge graph optimisation targets entity resolution — the process by which an AI system
          maps a name or concept to a specific, well-understood real-world object.
        </p>

        <p>
          When a user asks an AI assistant "who are the best GEO agencies in the UK?", the AI does not simply search for documents containing those words.
          It attempts to resolve the query to a set of known entities: organisations classified as GEO agencies, operating in the UK, with sufficient
          evidence of quality. The brands that are represented in the underlying knowledge graphs — with correct classifications, accurate attributes,
          and cross-referenced identifiers — are the brands that get named.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is the knowledge graph layer of <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/">generative engine optimisation</a>. It operates below the
          content layer and the technical layer. It is foundational: even the best-structured, most citable content will produce inconsistent
          AI citations if the underlying entity record is weak, ambiguous, or absent.
        </p>

        <h3>Knowledge Graphs vs. Traditional SEO Signals</h3>

        <p>
          Traditional SEO signals — backlinks, page authority, keyword density — tell search engines which pages are authoritative for a query.
          Knowledge graph signals tell AI systems which entities a page or brand represents, what category they belong to, and how they relate
          to other entities. These are different layers of the information architecture, and they require different strategies to optimise.
        </p>

        <p>
          A brand can hold the top organic position for "cloud accounting software" and still be absent from ChatGPT's response to
          "what are the best cloud accounting tools?" — because its entity record is incomplete, inconsistent, or absent from the knowledge bases
          that inform the AI's understanding of the category. Knowledge graph optimisation closes that gap.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="how-ai-uses-knowledge-graphs" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>How AI Systems Use Knowledge Graphs</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AI systems interact with knowledge graphs at two distinct points in the generation process: during training and during inference.</strong>
          Understanding both touchpoints is essential for prioritising knowledge graph optimisation efforts correctly.
        </p>

        <h3>Training-Time Representation</h3>

        <p>
          During the training of large language models, the training corpus includes extensive content from knowledge graph sources: Wikipedia articles,
          Wikidata dumps, DBpedia extracts, and structured data from across the web. Brands mentioned and described consistently in these sources
          are encoded into the model's weights — becoming part of what the model "knows" about the world without needing to retrieve external documents.
        </p>

        <p>
          This parametric representation matters for every AI system, including those that use retrieval-augmented generation, because the base
          model's understanding of an entity shapes how it interprets retrieved documents. A brand with strong parametric representation is described
          accurately even when the retrieved documents are sparse. A brand with weak parametric representation may be described incorrectly
          even when retrieved documents are present.
        </p>

        <h3>Inference-Time Entity Resolution</h3>

        <p>
          Some AI systems query knowledge graph APIs directly during inference. Google AI Overviews, for instance, integrates with Google's
          Knowledge Graph to resolve entity attributes when generating responses. When a user asks about a brand, the system may fetch the
          entity's Knowledge Graph entry to populate attributes — name, description, website, category — rather than relying solely on
          training data or retrieved documents.
        </p>

        <p>
          For these systems, a Knowledge Panel entry — Google's front-end representation of a Knowledge Graph entity — is a direct AI visibility
          signal. Brands with Knowledge Panels have a structured, verified entity record that AI Overviews can query. Brands without them
          depend entirely on the model's parametric knowledge and retrieved web content.
        </p>

        <h3>RAG and Entity Disambiguation</h3>

        <p>
          In retrieval-augmented generation pipelines, entity disambiguation is a pre-retrieval step: the system attempts to identify which
          real-world entity the query is about before fetching candidate documents. Knowledge graph signals help the system perform this
          disambiguation correctly. A brand with a clear entity record — consistent name, unique identifiers, unambiguous category classification —
          is disambiguated confidently. A brand whose name is shared with other entities, or whose category classification is inconsistent
          across sources, introduces ambiguity that can result in the wrong content being retrieved and the wrong brand being cited.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="knowledge-graph-signals" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>The Key Entity Signals</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Entity authority is built through a combination of structured data on your own site, third-party knowledge base presence, and consistent cross-platform signals.</strong>
            Each signal layer reinforces the others. The following are the highest-impact components of a knowledge graph optimisation programme.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Organisation Schema with Complete Attributes</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Your website's <code>Organization</code> JSON-LD markup is the primary structured signal about your entity on your own domain.
              A complete Organisation schema includes: legal name, trading name, founding date, country of incorporation, official website,
              industry classification using a recognised taxonomy, description, logo, contact details, and a comprehensive <code>sameAs</code> array.
              Incomplete or minimal Organisation markup is one of the most commonly missed opportunities in knowledge graph optimisation.
              See our <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-[var(--accent)] border-b border-[var(--accent)]/35 hover:border-[var(--accent)] transition">schema markup for AI search</a> guide for full implementation patterns.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Google Business Profile</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Google Business Profile is a direct input into Google's Knowledge Graph for local and regional organisations.
              A verified, complete Business Profile — with accurate primary category, consistent NAP (name, address, phone),
              detailed description, and active review management — signals to Google's entity systems that the organisation is
              real, active, and correctly classified. For brands targeting Google AI Overviews, Business Profile completeness
              correlates directly with Knowledge Panel presence.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Industry Directory and Database Presence</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Authoritative industry directories — Crunchbase, Companies House, sector-specific registries — provide structured
              entity data that both feeds AI training pipelines and serves as reference material for knowledge graph resolution.
              Critically, the entity attributes in these directories must be consistent with each other and with your website's
              schema markup. Any inconsistency — different trading names, conflicting founding dates, inconsistent category
              classifications — introduces ambiguity that AI systems resolve conservatively, often by omitting the brand.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Editorial Mentions in Authoritative Publications</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              References to your brand in established industry publications, research papers, and news sources serve as
              third-party corroboration of your entity's existence, category, and attributes. AI training pipelines weight
              authoritative editorial sources heavily. A brand mentioned in ten high-authority publications — with consistent
              name, description, and category — has significantly stronger parametric representation than a brand referenced
              only in its own content.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="wikidata-wikipedia" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Wikidata and Wikipedia: The Highest-Value Knowledge Graph Targets</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Wikidata and Wikipedia are disproportionately represented in AI training corpora, making them the highest-priority targets for any knowledge graph optimisation programme.</strong>
          Both are openly licensed, machine-readable, and trusted sources that feed dozens of downstream AI systems.
        </p>

        <h3>Creating a Wikidata Entry</h3>

        <p>
          Wikidata is an open knowledge base maintained by the Wikimedia Foundation. Any organisation that meets Wikidata's criteria for
          notability — typically demonstrated by verifiable references in reliable sources — can have an entry. A Wikidata item provides
          a persistent Q-number identifier that AI systems can use to resolve your entity unambiguously across all languages and contexts.
        </p>

        <p>
          A complete Wikidata entry for an organisation should include: official name (P1448), legal form (P1454), country (P17),
          official website (P856), founding date (P571), industry (P452), LinkedIn profile URL (P6linkedin), and references
          to external sources for each substantive claim. Every claim in Wikidata should be backed by a reference to a reliable source —
          unsourced claims are lower confidence and may be reviewed or removed.
        </p>

        <p>
          Once your Wikidata entry exists, reference its Q-number URL in your website's <code>sameAs</code> array and in your
          Wikipedia article's infobox (if applicable). This cross-referencing strengthens the entity resolution chain and is
          one of the clearest signals available to AI systems that these records describe the same organisation.
        </p>

        <h3>Wikipedia and AI Training Data</h3>

        <p>
          Wikipedia is among the most heavily weighted sources in LLM training datasets. Models trained on Common Crawl, The Pile,
          and similar corpora absorb Wikipedia articles in their entirety, and the entity descriptions, category memberships,
          and infobox attributes in those articles directly inform the model's parametric knowledge about organisations.
        </p>

        <p>
          Not every brand meets Wikipedia's notability guidelines, which require significant coverage in reliable, independent,
          secondary sources. For brands that do qualify, a well-maintained Wikipedia article — with accurate infobox data,
          reliable references, and correct category assignments — provides the single most impactful knowledge graph signal available.
        </p>

        <p>
          For brands that do not qualify for a standalone article, contributing to relevant category pages, industry overview articles,
          and "List of" pages can associate your brand with the correct topics and categories within Wikipedia's entity structure —
          providing partial knowledge graph coverage without requiring standalone article eligibility.
        </p>

        <h3>DBpedia and Linked Open Data</h3>

        <p>
          DBpedia is an automated extraction of structured data from Wikipedia infoboxes, published as Linked Open Data. Because
          DBpedia is generated from Wikipedia, maintaining accurate Wikipedia infobox data automatically improves DBpedia coverage.
          DBpedia feeds several AI training pipelines and knowledge graph systems that may not access Wikipedia directly, making
          it a valuable secondary signal that requires no additional action beyond maintaining Wikipedia accuracy.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="schema-markup" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Schema Markup and sameAs: Connecting Your Entity Across Platforms</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The <code>sameAs</code> property is the most direct technical mechanism for connecting your website's entity representation to external knowledge bases.</strong>
          It is a single JSON-LD property that can materially improve AI entity resolution and is deployable in a day.
        </p>

        <p>
          A <code>sameAs</code> array in your Organisation schema should reference every authoritative external record that describes your organisation:
          Wikidata Q-number URL, Wikipedia article URL, LinkedIn company page, Crunchbase profile, Companies House record, Google Business Profile,
          Twitter/X profile, Facebook page, and any sector-specific registry entries. Each reference reduces entity ambiguity by providing
          an additional data point that corroborates your brand's identity.
        </p>

        <p>
          Beyond <code>sameAs</code>, consider deploying these additional Organisation schema properties for maximum knowledge graph signal strength.
          For full implementation guidance, see our <a href="/schema-markup-ai/">schema markup for AI search</a> reference, and for
          broader entity strategy see our <a href="/geo-services/#entity-optimisation">entity optimisation service</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: Signal Comparison Table -->
