      <!-- Section 7: Common Errors -->
      <section id="common-errors" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Common Knowledge Graph Errors That Suppress AI Citations</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>The majority of brands have avoidable errors in their knowledge graph presence that directly suppress AI citations.</strong>
            These are the most frequently encountered issues in GEO audits, listed in order of frequency.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2" style="border-left-color: #ef4444;">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-red-400">Missing or Minimal Organisation Schema</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Many sites have no Organisation schema at all, or have only a minimal implementation with name and URL.
              Without a structured entity declaration on your own domain, AI systems have no machine-readable source of truth
              for your brand's attributes. Deploy a complete Organisation schema in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> of your
              homepage with all available attributes and a comprehensive <code>sameAs</code> array. This single change often
              produces the fastest improvement in AI entity resolution.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2" style="border-left-color: #f97316;">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-orange-400">Inconsistent Entity Data Across Sources</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Conflicting entity data across directories, social profiles, and structured markup is the most common
              knowledge graph problem and one of the hardest to fix at scale. When AI systems encounter a brand described
              as "GEOoptimised Ltd" on Companies House, "GEO Optimised" on LinkedIn, and "Geooptimised" on Crunchbase,
              they face a disambiguation problem. The conservative resolution is to reduce confidence in citations or
              omit the brand entirely. Conduct a full entity audit before any other knowledge graph work and standardise
              every attribute across every source.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2" style="border-left-color: #eab308;">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-yellow-400">No Wikidata Entry</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Wikidata is openly editable and does not require the level of notability that Wikipedia does.
              Most established businesses qualify for a Wikidata entry on the basis of Companies House registration
              and verifiable website presence alone. Yet the majority of SMEs and even many enterprise brands
              have no Wikidata entry. Creating one — with sourced claims and a Q-number — provides an unambiguous
              entity identifier that dramatically reduces the risk of AI misrepresentation.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6 border-l-2" style="border-left-color: #6366f1;">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-indigo-400">sameAs Array Points to Dead or Incorrect URLs</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              A common technical error is deploying a <code>sameAs</code> array that includes outdated URLs —
              old social profile addresses, redirected directory listings, or incorrect Wikidata Q-number URLs.
              AI systems that follow these references and encounter 404s or mismatched entities may reduce their
              confidence in the entity record. Audit every URL in your <code>sameAs</code> array quarterly
              and update any that have changed.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <p>
            A structured knowledge graph audit is the recommended starting point for any entity optimisation programme.
            Our <a href="/geo-services/#entity-optimisation">entity and knowledge graph optimisation</a> service covers all of these
            areas and benchmarks your entity authority against competitors and category leaders. Pair this with our
            <a href="/llms-txt/">llms.txt implementation guide</a> to ensure AI crawlers can access your most authoritative content.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

